Model using Data After 1997 Gives Better Results than My Previous Models

1. Data After 1997

Before 1997, Japanese active population grows. But after 1997, the population steadily decreases. Due to Japan’s low birth rates, together with little effective interventions for changing the status quo, many reports project Japan’s population will continue the downward trend for many years. If we know the population will decline, why don’t we focus on the recent declining population data after 1997.
The 20% test set data of the entire series start on Sep 2005. In order to match the starting data for forecasting, I reserve 47.7% of the data after 1997 for training. So the training set starts in Jan 1997 and ends in Aug 2005. The test set starts in Sep 2005 annd ends in Feb 2015.

This chart shows a decline trend with seasonality. The ACF and PACF suggests this series might have an AR(2) effect. This series doesn’t pass the ADF test of stationarity, nor the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags.

2. Models

Since the downward trend looks quite linear, I model the series with a linear trend and a quadratic trend. The RMSE comparison tables are below. Linear trend with seasonality has the lowest RMSE, 324 thousand people. This value is smaller than my previous models’.

3. Analyze Model: Linear Trend with Seasonality

Although this model has the best RMSE, its residuals don’t pass the ADF test of stationarity, nor the Box-Ljung test of independence up to 24 lags. Additionally, the ACF and PACF suggest some ARMA effects.
